\begin{block}{Discussion}
\begin{figure}
\vspace{-1em}
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{../fig/cycle_example.pdf}
\caption{\textbf{Closer look at Red Queen dynamics}. (left) interaction between parasites and sexual hosts can create various oscillations. (right) we expect to see a downward curved trend but accounting for oscillations in each population predicts an oppsite trend}
\vspace{-1.5em}
\end{figure}
\begin{itemize}
    \item eventually parasites evolves to infect resistant snail and sexual reproduction decrease in the population; creates \textbf{oscillation between parasite and sexual population} (left panel)
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

\begin{alertblock}{Conclusion and further questions}
\vspace{0.05em}
\begin{itemize}
    \item sexual population "runs away" (to escape infection) from parasites but parasites "chase" (to infect more) sexual populations, creating an oscillation; depending on where the population is in the cycle, we can observe a wide range of trends
    \item what kind of data and tests are needed to detect oscillation in the population?
\end{itemize}
\end{alertblock}


